segments. The presence of a greater than 50% diameter reduction residual 
stenosis predicted further restenosis and late clinical failure (11% success 
rate at 1 year). When the degree of residual stenosis at the percutaneous 
transluminal angioplasty site was less than 50% diameter reduction by duplex 
scanning, the procedure was durable (80% success rate at 2 years), even in 
patients with critical ischemia, poor runoff, or diabetes mellitus.

